rleden","1303–Female":"1303–Overleden","1359":"1359","1403":"1403","1303":"1303","1313":"1313","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1318":"1318","Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bromley, London, England":"Bromley, London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England or France":"Frances, Pacific, Washington, Verenigde Staten van Amerika"},"en":{"1330–1370":"1330–1370","1313–1359":"1313–1359","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1298–Male":"1298–Deceased","1303–Female":"1303–Deceased","1359":"1359","1403":"1403","1303":"1303","1313":"1313","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1318":"1318","Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Bromley, London, England":"Bromley, London, England, United Kingdom","England or France":"Frances, Pacific, Washington, United States","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bromley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Bromley, in Essex, Hertfordshire, Kent (now in Greater London), Greater London, Greater Manchester, Staffordshire, Shropshire, and elsewhere. Most are named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, but Bromley (near Bow) in Greater London is from Old English <i>bræmbel</i> ‘bramble’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Brimley","meanings":["habitational name, perhaps from Brimley in Devon or Brimbley in Stoke Abbott, Dorset, both named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","variant of   Bromley  .","English:"]},{"name":"Brumley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bromley  . This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Bromley was born in 1330, in Bromley, London, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Thomas Bromley, was 32 and her mother, Mrs. Lady Thomas Bromley, was 27. She married Elias Broughton in 1359, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1370, in Frances, Pacific, Washington, United States, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1330–1370":"1330–1370","1313–1359":"1313–1359","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1359":"1359","1403":"1403","1303":"1303","1313":"1313","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1318":"1318","